    short: 'Re-attempt a failed roll by describing what extra you do — but a failed push has a real, worse consequence.',
    body: 'After a **failed** roll, you may **push** it: describe what you are doing differently or harder — taking more time, forcing the door instead of picking it, pressing the witness who has already said no — and roll **again** against the same target.\n\nThe Keeper must agree the justification is real. Pushing is not a free reroll; it is a bargain. **If the pushed roll also fails, the Keeper introduces a serious consequence**, not just "nothing happens". The door opens onto the thing you did not want to meet; the witness calls the police; the rope you strained gives way at the worst point.\n\nRestrictions worth knowing at the table:\n\n· A **fumble** cannot be pushed.\n· You get **one push per roll** — you cannot push a push.\n· **Luck cannot be spent to save a failed pushed roll.**\n\nPushing is the game\'s pressure valve and its trap at once: it is how investigators find the clue the scenario needs, and how they walk into the room that kills them.',
