    body: '**Luck** is rolled **3d6 × 5** like a characteristic, but it behaves like a **currency**. After you see a failed roll, you may **spend Luck points one-for-one to reduce the rolled result** until it reaches a success level. Roll 58 against a skill of 50? Spend **8 Luck** and it becomes a Regular success.\n\nSpent Luck is **gone** — the pool does not refresh at the end of the session the way a d20 game\'s resources do. It is regained slowly, via a **Luck recovery check** between scenarios (roll d100 above your current Luck to gain **1d10**) and via Keeper awards.\n\nWhat Luck **cannot** do — this is the list that matters at the table:\n\n· It cannot be spent on **damage rolls**.\n· It cannot be spent on **Sanity rolls**.\n· It cannot be spent on **Luck rolls** themselves.\n· It cannot rescue a **failed pushed roll**.\n· It cannot turn a **fumble** into anything.\n\nLuck is also rolled *as* a characteristic — a **Luck roll** — when the Keeper needs to know whether pure chance favours you: is the shop still open, was the car left unlocked, which investigator does the thing notice first.',
